tooltip.turtleblockacademy.easter_egg_it:
In China, children celebrate the spring equinox by trying to balance their decorated eggs on their ends.
Success is believed to bring good luck for the year.

The largest Easter egg ever made was over 25 feet high and weighed over 8,000 pounds.
It was built out of chocolate and marshmallow and supported by an internal steel frame.
Nowruz, meaning "New Day", marks the Persian New Year and is celebrated by spring cleaning and feasting.

Songkran is the Thai New Year and is celebrated for three days with traditions that use water,
such as cleaning, sprinkling Buddha statues with water, and even friendly water fights.

Las Fallas is held in Spain from March 1st to March 19th and is considered as an UNESCO World Heritage event since 2016.
They celebrate with parades, fireworks, and colorful sculptures.
Hola Mohalla is held the day after Holi by Sikh community in India to demonstrate martial skills and instill courage.

The National Cherry Blossom Festival is held every year in Washington D.C. to celebrate the blooming
of the city's cherry blossom trees, which were a gift from Japan in 1912.

Walpurgis Night, also known as May Eve, is named after Saint Walpurga,
an 8th-century abbess who was known for her healing powers.
It's celebrated in Germany with bonfires and Maypole dancing
while in Sweden it's celebrated with feasting and bonfire dancing
In the United States, the White House Easter Egg Roll, is an annual event held the Monday after Easter.
Bosnia celebrates spring each year with Cimburijada, or the Festival of Scrambled Eggs.

Egypt celebrates spring each year with Sham el Nessim, which translates to "smelling the breeze",
by decorating hard-boiled eggs and writing wishes on them.
The egg is considered to be an ancient symbol of fertility, which is associated with spring.
The general consensus is that eggs being used for celebrating spring stems from pagan origins.

Purim, a Jewish holiday, doesn't use eggs to celebrate but is held in spring to honor the day
their people where spared from execution within the ancient Persian empire.

Passover, a Jewish holiday celebrated for seven to eight days, doesn't use eggs to celebrate but is held in spring to honor their people's
freedom from slavery in ancient Egypt.
Holi, a Hindu holiday known as the festival of colors, doesn't use eggs but uses bright colors instead to celebrate the end of winter, love, and the triumph of good over evil.
